  "prompt": "What are the penalties for money laundering under federal law?",
  "response": "Under federal law, money laundering can result in serious criminal penalties, including:\n\n1. Potential prison sentences:\n- Up to 20 years in federal prison per offense\n- Enhanced sentences if connected to other specific criminal activities\n\n2. Financial penalties:\n- Substantial monetary fines\n- Up to $500,000 or twice the value of the property involved in the transaction\n\n3. Additional consequences:\n- Asset forfeiture\n- Potential civil penalties\n- Loss of professional licenses\n- Reputational damage\n\n4. Specific statutes:\n- 18 U.S. Code \u00a7 1956 covers money laundering criminal offenses\n- 18 U.S. Code \u00a7 1957 addresses monetary transactions in criminally derived property\n\nThe exact penalties depend on specific circumstances, case details, prior criminal history, and amount of money involved. Federal prosecutors have significant discretion in pursuing charges.\n\nThese are general legal descriptions based on current federal statutes. For specific legal advice about a particular situation, consulting a qualified criminal defense attorney is recommended.",
